Overview

The following report examines growth data of two dominant palmetto species (Serenoa repens and Sabal etonia) in South Florida to produce a binomial logistic regression model that classifies plant species based on several physical features of the plant. First, differences between the species are visualized to determine which variables will be useful in classifying species. Then, the model is evaluated using 10-fold cross validation and AIC. Finally, the model is applied to the data to determine its efficacy in predicting plant species.

Data Citation: Data source: Abrahamson, W.G. 2019. Survival, growth and biomass estimates of two dominant palmetto species of south-central Florida from 1981 - 2017, ongoing at 5-year intervals ver 1. Environmental Data Initiative. https://doi.org/10.6073/pasta/f2f96ec76fbbd4b9db431c79a770c4d5

Reading in and cleaning up the data

palmetto <- read_csv(here("data", "palmetto.csv")) %>% 
  select(height, length, width, green_lvs, species) %>% # selecting for plant height (height), canopy length (length), canopy width (width), and number of green leaves (green_lvs)
# 1 = Serenoa repens, 2 = Sabal etonia
  drop_na() %>% # dropping NA values
  mutate(species_name = case_when(
    species == 1 ~ "Serenoa repens", # new column for species name
    species == 2 ~ "Sabal etonia"
  )) %>% 
  mutate(species_name = as_factor(species_name)) # changing species name to a factor for use in blr

Variables of interest: - Number of green leaves - green_lvs

  • Height of plant (cm) - height

  • Width of canopy (cm) - width

  • Length of canopy (cm) - length

Fig. 1 compares two palmetto species to determine feasibility of each of four variables in predicting whether a plant is Serenoa repens (green) or Sabal etonia (orange). Variables examined in the figure are: number of green leaves on the plant (top left), height of plant (cm) (top right), canopy width (cm) (bottom left) and canopy length (cm) (bottom right). Width of the shape in each figure represents the quantity of observations at that particular value. Box endpoints indicate the 25th and 75th percentile values; the black line and black point within the box indicate the median and mean value for each species, respectively.

Conclusion: Based on this visualization, it appears that number of green leaves and canopy length will be useful in correctly classifying species, since there is a noticeable difference in the mean, median and overall spread of the data. Plant height and canopy width differ only very slightly between the two species, and thus will be less useful in classifying the species of plant.

Binomial logistic regression

Running BLR for two models:

  • Model 1: Plant species as a function of plant height, number of green leaves, canopy width and canopy length

  • Model 2: Plant species as a function of plant height, number of green leaves, and canopy width

# storing functions of combinations of variables for use in regression
f1 <- species_name ~ height + length + width + green_lvs
f2 <- species_name ~ height + width + green_lvs

# running and storing the regressions for each formula
blr1 <- glm(formula = f1,
            data = palmetto,
            family = "binomial")

blr2 <- glm(formula = f2,
            data = palmetto,
            family = "binomial")

# taking a look at the outputs of the regression with summary()
# reference (0) = Sabal etonia

Model Selection

AIC

aic <- aictab(list(blr1, blr2))
# model1 = 5194
# model2 = 5987

Model 1: 5194.6

Model 2: 5987.5

The difference in AICc is very large (792.9), thus model 1 has significantly better fit than model 2.

10-fold cross validation

set.seed(24) # setting seed for reproducibility

tr_ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 10) # stroing train control, specifying 10 folds

# train the model
model1 <- train(f1, data = palmetto,
                method = "glm",
                family = "binomial",
                trControl = tr_ctrl)
# accuracy = 0.917

# train the other model
model2 <- train(f2, data = palmetto,
                method = "glm",
                family = "binomial",
                trControl = tr_ctrl)
# accuracy = 0.899

Model assessment results: Model 1, which classifies palmetto species as a function of plant height, canopy width, canopy length and number of green leaves, performed better during 10-fold cross validation (accuracy = 91.7%, AICc = 5194.6) than model 2 (accuracy = 89.9%, AICc = 5987.5). Thus, based on the prediction accuracy results and AIC values, model 1 is preferred.

Regression results

Table 1 shows the results of binomial logistic regression for model 1. Coefficients show the change in log odds of the resulting species being Sabal etonia (reference) as opposed to Serenoa repens.

# storing the results of regression as a data frame
blr1_tidy <- tidy(blr1) %>%  
  mutate(p.value = case_when( # finalizing p.values for table
    p.value <0.001 ~ "<0.001"
  )) %>% 
  mutate(term = case_when( # finalizing variable names for table
         term == "(Intercept)" ~ "Intercept",
         term == "height" ~ "Height",
         term == "length" ~ "Length",
         term == "width" ~ "Width",
         term == "green_lvs" ~ "# of green leaves")) %>% 
  select(-statistic)

# finalizing table
kable(blr1_tidy,

  kable_minimal(full_width = FALSE)

Model success rate

Table 1 shows the success rate of the chosen model in classifying each plant species when trained on and applied to the whole data set.

# storing a function for prediction accuracy
prediction_accuracy <- function(x, y) {
  accurate <- ifelse(x == y, 1, 0)
  return(accurate)
}

# creating a new dataframe with predictions based on our model
# could also use augment() here: palmetto_augment <- blr1 %>% augment(type.predict = "response") 
palmetto_success <- palmetto %>% 
  mutate(chances_sabal = predict(blr1, # adding a new column for the probability that the species is sabal, given our model
                   palmetto,
                   type = "response")) %>% 
  mutate(predicted = ifelse(chances_sabal >= .50, "Sabal etonia", "Serenoa repens")) %>%  # adding a new column that predicts the species based on the probability, using 50% as the threshold
  mutate(accurate = prediction_accuracy(species_name, predicted))

# creating a final table for model prediction accuracy for each plant

accuracy_table <- palmetto_success %>% 
  group_by(species_name) %>% # grouping by species
  summarize(observations = n(),
    total_accurate = sum(accurate), # finding total accurate predictions
            total_inaccurate = n() - sum(accurate), # total inaccurate predictions
            accuracy = (mean(accurate))*100,) # accuracy %

# finalized table with kable
kable(accuracy_table, digits = 1, col.names = c("Palmetto Species", "Total Observations", "Accurate", "Inaccurate", "% Accurate ")) %>% 
  kable_minimal(full_width = FALSE)
Palmetto Species Total Observations Accurate Inaccurate % Accurate
Serenoa repens 6112 5548 564 90.8
Sabal etonia 6155 5701 454 92.6

Conclusion: Model 1 (species as a function of plant height, canopy width, canopy length, and number of green leaves) is highly effective in classifying a plant as either Sabal etonia (92.6%, n = 6155) or Serenoa repens (90.8%, n = 6112).
